Class State

  • java.lang.Object
    • kariminf.faris.philosophical.Being
      • kariminf.faris.philosophical.State

  • public class State
extends Being
    Having or state, condition (ἔχειν, echein, to have or be). The examples Aristotle gives indicate that he meant a condition of rest resulting from an affection (i.e. being acted on): ‘shod’, ‘armed’. The term is, however, frequently taken to mean the determination arising from the physical accoutrements of an object: one's shoes, one's arms, etc. Traditionally, this category is also called a habitus (from Latin habere, to have).

      • affectState

        public boolean affectState(Action action,
                           QuantSubstance owner,
                           java.util.List<java.util.List<QuantSubstance>> relatives,
                           kariminf.sentrep.univ.types.Relation.Relative affectionType)
        Parameters:
        action - the action which represents a state. This action must not have subjects or objects.
        Example: a car which is stopped on the road and have an old engine. The car have two states: "stopped" and "having old engine".
        haver - The substance which have this state
        relatives - The subjects or the objects that share this action with the haver. If the haver is a subject, the relatives are objects, and vis-versa.
        affected - if SUBJECT then the haver is a subject, otherwise it is an object
        Returns:
        true if the affectation is successful
